g \\\"dst through symlinks\\\" - FIXED. Comment now clarifies: \\\"Only the parent directory is resolved; the final component may not exist yet.\\\"\\n    14→- [x] `prePromptStateFile` and `preTaskStateFile` nearly dead code - FIXED. Moved to `state_test.go` as test-only helpers with clear comments.\\n    15→\\n    16→## New Findings\\n    17→\\n    18→### Critical (Must Fix)\\n    19→\\n    20→None.\\n    21→\\n    22→### Important (Should Fix)\\n    23→\\n    24→- **[cmd/entire/cli/session/state.go:377-384] `Clear` still falls back to `os.Remove` when `os.OpenRoot` fails.** This was flagged as a Suggestion in review-01, but it deserves a bit more scrutiny. After adding `ValidateSessionID` (which prevents traversal via the session ID itself), the fallback is less dangerous -- the `filepath.Glob` pattern uses a validated session ID, so the matched files will be legitimate. However, the silent fallback means that if `os.OpenRoot` fails for reasons other than \\\"directory doesn't exist\\\" (e.g., permissions), the code silently degrades to non-root-scoped removal without any logging. Consider at minimum adding a `logging.Warn()` call when falling back, so operators can diagnose unexpected `os.OpenRoot` failures. This is not blocking.\\n    25→\\n    26→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n    27→\\n    28→- **[cmd/entire/cli/utils.go:98-108] `openAllowedRoot` still duplicates `paths.IsSubpath` logic.** This was noted in review-01. The inline comment explains the rationale (avoiding a redundant `filepath.Rel` call). Acceptable as-is, but if `IsSubpath` gains edge-case fixes in the future, this copy would drift. A `paths.IsSubpathFromRel(rel string) bool` helper would centralize the check. Low priority.\\n    29→\\n    30→- **[cmd/entire/cli/session/state.go:339-362] Atomic write uses `os.Root` for the temp file but `os.Rename` with `stateFilePath` for the rename.** This is documented in the comment (\\\"Rename is not available on os.Root, so we keep using os.Rename\\\") and the paths are validated via `ValidateSessionID`, so the approach is sound. Just noting that this is a known limitation of `os.Root` and the fallback is properly guarded by input validation.\\n    31→\\n    32→- **[cmd/entire/cli/osroot/osroot.go:40-51] `WriteFile` does not call `f.Sync()` before close.** This was noted in review-01. For the session state atomic-write path this is mitigated by the rename pattern, but for other callers (metadata writes, rewind file restoration), a crash between write and close could produce partial files. Low risk in practice.\\n    33→\\n    34→### Praise\\n    35→\\n    36→- All five critical and important items from review-01 have been properly addressed. The dead code is gone, validation is in place at every entry point, comments are accurate, and test helpers are correctly scoped to test files.\\n    37→- The `osroot` package is clean and well-tested, with traversal attacks, symlink escapes, and normal operations all covered.\\n    38→- Good use of `paths.IsSubpath` to replace ad-hoc prefix checks in `isProtectedPath` and `IsInfrastructurePath` -- consistent abstraction.\\n    39→- The `IsSubpath` tests are thorough, covering traversal attacks, relative paths, prefix-but-not-subpath cases, and edge cases.\\n    40→- The `openAllowedRoot` / `allowedRootDirs` / `appendResolved` decomposition is clean and testable.\\n    41→- Proper handling of `os.IsNotExist` throughout -- the code correctly distinguishes \\\"directory doesn't exist yet\\\" from other errors, returning nil/nil for the former.\\n    42→\\n    43→## Summary\\n    44→\\n    45→- **Overall assessment: APPROVE**\\n    46→- All critical and important items from review-01 have been addressed correctly.\\n    47→- The remaining suggestions are minor (fallback logging, code duplication, fsync) and none are blocking.\\n    48→- The implementation provides meaningful security hardening through kernel-enforced directory scoping via `os.Root`, with proper input validation as def