uid\":\"021ab8f7-0354-4609-b80e-6d8552ee061e\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"PostToolUse\",\"hookName\":\"PostToolUse:Agent\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code post-task\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01DshmUkPhsUufSE6R4pqoEZ\",\"toolUseID\":\"toolu_01DshmUkPhsUufSE6R4pqoEZ\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-16T14:43:41.821Z\",\"uuid\":\"0d203e21-0c51-4b28-ba7a-e9150609f08b\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"c42b5c72-c49c-4b74-8715-bfd38547eb46\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/os-root-traversal-resistant\",\"slug\":\"radiant-wondering-turtle\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"4c18b372-2638-4801-989c-50e47613f8b0\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"promptId\":\"ac31f79d-9a0c-4e20-9117-0a4307bdc57e\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01DshmUkPhsUufSE6R4pqoEZ\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Now I have enough context. Here are my findings.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Efficiency Analysis: os.Root Usage in This Diff\\n\\n### Concern 1: Repeated os.OpenRoot calls in state.go (Capture/Load/Cleanup)\\n\\n**Verdict: Not meaningful overhead.**\\n\\nIn `state.go`, `CapturePrePromptState`, `LoadPrePromptState`, and `CleanupPrePromptState` each open their own `os.Root` handle to `paths.EntireTmpDir`. These are called from `lifecycle.go` in sequence during a session turn: Capture at prompt start (~line 204), Load at stop (~line 343), and Cleanup after processing (~lines 442/497).\\n\\n`os.OpenRoot` is a single `openat2` syscall (Linux) or `open` with `O_DIRECTORY` (macOS). The cost is comparable to a single `stat()` call -- on the order of microseconds. Three such calls per session turn is negligible when the surrounding operations include git status computation, tree building, JSON marshaling, and file I/O.\\n\\nRefactoring to share a handle across these three functions would require either (a) threading an `*os.Root` parameter through the call chain, or (b) adding a struct to hold the handle with lifecycle management. Both add complexity that is not justified by the savings. The functions are called at different lifecycle phases (start vs. stop of a turn), so holding a directory fd open across potentially minutes of agent work would be the wrong trade-off -- you'd be holding a kernel resource longer to save microseconds.\\n\\n**Assessment: Current approach is fine. No action needed.**\\n\\n### Concern 2: Save() holds os.Root open through os.Rename\\n\\n**Verdict: Not a concern.**\\n\\nIn `session/state.go` `Save()`, the code opens `os.Root`, writes a temp file via `osroot.WriteFile`, then the deferred `root.Close()` runs after `os.Rename` completes. The root handle is held open for the duration of one JSON write + one rename -- both are sub-millisecond operations on local filesystems.\\n\\nThe alternative would be to explicitly close the root before the rename:\\n\\n```go\\nroot.Close()  // explicit close before rename\\nos.Rename(tmpFile, stateFile)\\n```\\n\\nThis would save holding one directory fd for the duration of a rename call. The savings is on the order of tens of microseconds. The `defer` pattern is more readable and less error-prone (no risk of forgetting to close on error paths).\\n\\nOne correctness note: the `os.Rename` operates on paths constructed via `s.stateFilePath()` which joins `s.stateDir` with the filename. Since `os.Rename` is not available on `os.Root`, this is the correct approach. The open root handle does not interfere with the rename -- they are independent kernel operations.\\n\\n**Assessment: Current approach is correct and idiomatic. No action needed.**\\n\\n### Concern 3: Rewind reuses a single os.Root handle (could state.go do the same?)\\n\\n**Verdict: Correct observation about rewind; state.go cannot easily follow the same pattern.**\\n\\nThe rewind code in `manual_commit_rewind.go` opens one `os.Root` at the repo root and reuses it for all file deletions and writes during a rewind operation. This is the right pattern because rewind is a single atomic-feeling operation that touches many files in rapid succession.\\n\\nThe state.go functions (`Capture`, `Load`, `Cleanup`) cannot easily follow this pattern because:\\n\\n1. They are called at **different lifecycle phases** -- Capture at turn start, Load/Cleanup at turn end. Holding a handle across these would mean keeping it open for the entire duration of an agent turn (potentially minutes or hours).\\n\\n2. They are **separate exported functions** called independently from `lifecycle.go`. Sharing a handle would require a struct or context-based handle pool, adding abstraction for no practical gain.\\n\\n3. The `session/state.go` `StateStore` *could* theoretically hold a cached `*os.Root` on the struct, but the `StateStore` is long-lived (created once per session). Caching the handle would mean holding a directory fd for the entire session lifetime, which is unnecessary and could cause issues if the directory is recreated.\\n\\nThe one place where consolidation *would* be natural is `session/state.go` `Save()` + `Clear()` if they were ever called in sequence -- but they are not (Save is called during session updates; Clear is called on session end).\\n\\n**Assessment: The rewind pattern is good where it is. The state.go separation is architecturally correct.**\\n\\n### Concern 4: allowedRootDirs() calls filepath.EvalSymlinks on every copyFile call\\n\\n**Verdict: Not a concern in practice, but worth noting for documentation.**\\n\\n`allowedRootDirs()` is called from `openAllowedRoot()`, which is called from `copyFile()`. Each call resolves symlinks for up to 3 directories (repo root, home dir, temp dir). `filepath.EvalSymlinks` does `lstat` calls for each path component, so for a 4-component path like `/private/var/folders/xx/...`, that is ~4 `lstat` syscalls per directory, or ~12 total syscalls per `copyFile` invocation.\\n\\nLooking at callers, `copyFile` is called from:\\n- `metadata.go:103` -- copying a transcript file (once per checkpoint save)\\n- `rewind.go:652` -- copying a session file (once per rewind)\\n\\nSo this runs at most a handful of times per session lifecycle. Even at 12 `lstat` calls each, the total is well under 100 microseconds per invocation. The surrounding operations (reading/writing files, git operations) dwarf this cost by orders of magnitude.\\n\\nIf `copyFile` were ever called in a tight loop over many files, caching the result of `allowedRootDirs()` would make sense. But at current call frequencies, caching would be premature optimization that adds state management complexity (cache invalidation if CWD changes, etc.).\\n\\n**Assessment: Not a concern at current call frequencies. If copyFile ever becomes hot-path, cache allowedRootDirs at the call site, not globally.**\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\nAll four concerns examine real overhead, but in every case the cost is negligible relative to the surrounding operations. The pattern choices are architecturally sound:\\n\\n| Concern | Overhead | Frequency | Verdict |\\n|---------|----------|-----------|---------|\\n| 3x os.OpenRoot in state.go | ~microseconds each | Once per turn | Fine |\\n| Root held during Rename | ~tens of microseconds | Once per save | Fine |\\n| Rewind reuse vs state.go | N/A (different architecture) | N/A | Correctly different |\\n| EvalSymlinks in allowedRootDirs | ~12 lstat calls | 1-2x per session | Fine |\\n\\nNo changes recommended. The code prioritizes correctness and readability over micro-optimization, which is the right trade-off for a CLI tool where these paths execute a handful of times per user interaction.\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"agentId: a89c05f53d773f794 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\\n<usage>total_tokens: 45999\\ntool_uses: 6\\nduration_ms: 66095</usage>\"}]}]},\"uuid\":\"6ec9dca0-f171-4109-a433-a8a6a2efd3f7\",\